        "description": "Openmix Application Development Tool\n====================================\n\n**This project is currently in a planning/pre-Alpha stage.**\n\n.. This will eventually work, once we've sent a release to the prod repo.\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/opxtool.svg\n    :target: https://pypi.org/project/opxtool/\n\n.. These will eventually work, once we've tagged a release on Github...\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/github/release/gratopia/opxtool.svg\n    :target: https://github.com/gratopia/opxtool/releases\n\n.. This will work once we get rolling with Travis CI...\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/travis/gratopia/opxtool.svg\n    :target: https://travis-ci.org/gratopia/opxtool\n\nOpenmix is a software-defined DNS load-balancing system, developed and delivered by Cedexis_ [1]_. In a typical scenario, you create a CNAME for your domain to a Cedexis Openmix application CNAME. When a request for your domain hits the application, it is responsible for answering with another CNAME (or a set of one or more A/AAAA records). In this way, the application can route between two or more delivery networks, or other infrastructure resources, often based on near real-time real-user performance data provided by `Cedexis Radar`_.\n\nTo create an Openmix application, you can either choose a \"quickstart\" application in the Cedexis portal, or upload a custom JavaScript application based on the Openmix API [2]_. Quickstart applications perform very well and are sufficient most of time. However, if you have a complex use case and need access to the wide array of options provided by the API, or if you simply prefer to control the software directly, a custom JavaScript application remains a good option.\n\nA trivial Openmix app written in JavaScript can be quite simple.\n\n.. code-block:: javascript\n\n    function onRequest(_, response) {\n        response.addARecord('1.2.3.4');\n    }\n\nHowever, real world apps generally do quite a bit more.\n\nOpxtool is a command-line utility used to generate and maintain Openmix applications. It is configuration-driven, meaning that you can avoid writing any JavaScript if you don't want to. Through a configuration file, you can compose an application declaratively. You can also specify a body of input data and expected results in order to test it. *The goal is to allow us to reason about an application's configuration, rather than its implementation in JavaScript.*\n\nFeatures available for inclusion in Openmix apps generated by the tool are provided by plugins. The tool comes with a set of reference plugins that should satisfy many use cases, but you can install more with ``pip``, or create your own. For more information, see `Plugins`_.\n\nUsage::\n\n    $ opxtool <operation> <arguments>\n\nOperations\n----------\n\nThis is an overview of some of the basic operations. More information is available by running ``opxtool --help`` or by reading the documentation_.\n\ninit\n^^^^\n\nInitialize a new application in the specified subdirectory relative to the working directory. The destination subdirectory must *not* already exist.\n\nExample::\n\n    $ opxtool init my-new-application\n\ntestconfig\n^^^^^^^^^^\n\nValidate the application configuration file.\n\nvalidate\n^^^^^^^^\n\nTODO\n\ntest\n^^^^\n\nTODO\n\nbuild\n^^^^^\n\nTODO\n\nplugins\n^^^^^^^\n\nTODO\n\nDocumentation\n-------------\n\nYou can read more about opxtool at https://gratopia.github.io/opxtool.\n\nLicense\n-------\n\nOpxtool is distributed under the terms of the `MIT <LICENSE.rst>`_ license.\n\nDistributed with opxtool is a copy of the Google Closure Compiler, which uses the `Apache License, Version 2.0 <https://github.com/google/closure-compiler/blob/master/COPYING>`_.\n\n-----\n\n.. Footnotes\n\n.. [1] It supports HTTP load-balancing for video streaming optimization as well.\n.. [2] You can read more about the Openmix API on the `Openmix App Library Wiki <https://github.com/cedexis/openmixapplib/wiki/Openmix-API>`_.\n\n.. Links\n\n.. _Cedexis: https://www.cedexis.com\n.. _`Cedexis Radar`: https://www.cedexis.com/radar/\n.. _`Plugins`: https://gratopia.github.io/opxtool/plugins\n\n",
